    {
        "content": "<p>When you want to enrich in a category, a good base of enrichment usually consists of a symmetric closed monoidal category, perhaps also requiring limits or colimits. If the category you want to enrich in lacks this structure, it becomes difficult to describe a consistent Yoneda theory for categories enriched in it, and do all the things you ordinarily would want to do in category theory. </p>\n<p>So here's my question: why can't you \"enrich\" in an arbitrary category C, perhaps a monoidal category without these key structures, simply by enriching instead in its presheaf category [C^op, Set]? After all, presheaf categories are toposes, so they have all the good properties you would want from a base of enrichment. The only requirement would then to ensure that all hom functors from categories enriched in [C^op, Set] into [C^op, Set] land in the image of the yoneda embedding C -&gt; [C^op, Set] so that all hom objects can be thought of as being objects of C.</p>",
        "id": 436706732,
        "sender_full_name": "John Onstead",
        "timestamp": 1714659900
    },
    {
        "content": "<blockquote>\n<p>So here's my question: why can't you \"enrich\" in an arbitrary category C, perhaps a monoidal category without these key structures, simply by enriching instead in its presheaf category [C^op, Set]?</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>You can, and this leads naturally to the notion of <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/locally%20graded%20category\">[[locally graded category]]</a>.</p>",
        "id": 436721592,
        "sender_full_name": "Nathanael Arkor",
        "timestamp": 1714664125
    },
    {
        "content": "<blockquote>\n<p>If the category you want to enrich in lacks this structure, it becomes difficult to describe a consistent Yoneda theory for categories enriched in it, and do all the things you ordinarily would want to do in category theory.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Although I would also counter this: I think it is an easy impression to get, because most authors work with a lot of structure on their bases of enrichment for convenience, but category theory behaves well even without all of these assumptions. One of the main obstructions it that a lot of the basic theory has not been developed (e.g. to the level of Kelly's <em>Basic concepts</em>), which makes it inconvenient to do.</p>",
        "id": 436722220,
        "sender_full_name": "Nathanael Arkor",
        "timestamp": 1714664305
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>(This is one of the motivations for developing formal category theory.)</p>",
        "id": 436722348,
        "sender_full_name": "Nathanael Arkor",
        "timestamp": 1714664340
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Thanks, this seems to answer the question. I have heard of a \"locally graded category\" before. but I suppose I hadn't connected these two ideas together! I'll certainly have to check out more about them and what they can be used for.</p>",
        "id": 436783616,
        "sender_full_name": "John Onstead",
        "timestamp": 1714687261
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>It's not true that you can enrich in an interesting way over an arbitrary monoidal category, and I expect that may remain the case even if one extends to presheaves. See <a href=\"https://mathoverflow.net/a/452029/95129\">this MO answer</a> I wrote about the fact that enrichment sometimes trivialises. Of course there will be at least some morphisms to consider once you take presheaves on <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>V</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">V</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">V</span></span></span></span>, so I'll be interested to hear if that gives some non-trivial categories or if you just end up being essentially Set-enriched.</p>",
        "id": 436823262,
        "sender_full_name": "Morgan Rogers (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1714716769
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Sorry I'm late. Just to note following your original question <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"673117\">@John Onstead</span> that even Kelly does indeed suggest to use this Yoneda universe enlargement at the end of Ch 2 and spelt out in 3.11 of <a href=\"http://www.tac.mta.ca/tac/reprints/articles/10/tr10.pdf\">Basic concepts</a>.</p>",
        "id": 438746765,
        "sender_full_name": "Sam Staton",
        "timestamp": 1715760127
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"277473\">@Morgan Rogers (he/him)</span> it's a nice illustration in your MO post. I agree that enrichment in <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">F</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">t</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">j</mi></mrow></msub></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathrm{FinSet}_{\\mathrm{bij}}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.9694em;vertical-align:-0.2861em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">FinSet</span></span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3361em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathrm mtight\">bij</span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.2861em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> is useless. However, enrichment in <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">[</mo><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">F</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">t</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">j</mi></mrow></msub><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">t</mi></mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">]</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">[\\mathrm{FinSet}_{\\mathrm{bij}},\\mathbf{Set}]</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.0361em;vertical-align:-0.2861em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">[</span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">FinSet</span></span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3361em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathrm mtight\">bij</span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.2861em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbf\">Set</span></span><span class=\"mclose\">]</span></span></span></span> is really useful. For example, a <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/PROP\">PROP</a> can be regarded as the same thing as an <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/enriched+monad\">enriched monad</a> on <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">[</mo><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">F</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">t</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">j</mi></mrow></msub><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">t</mi></mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">]</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">[\\mathrm{FinSet}_{\\mathrm{bij}},\\mathbf{Set}]</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.0361em;vertical-align:-0.2861em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">[</span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">FinSet</span></span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3361em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathrm mtight\">bij</span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.2861em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbf\">Set</span></span><span class=\"mclose\">]</span></span></span></span> that is commutative and preserves colimits. Maybe this is the kind of non-trivial example you were looking for.<br>\n(I found this angle on PROPs useful because it suggested to weaken the colimit preservation requirement to sifted-colimit preservation. This gives an algebraic framework combining features of both Lawvere theories and PROPs, which I used for presenting quantum theory, <a href=\"http://www.cs.ox.ac.uk/people/samuel.staton/papers/popl2015.pdf\">here</a>. That set-up is also <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">[</mo><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">F</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">t</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">j</mi></mrow></msub><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">t</mi></mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">]</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">[\\mathrm{FinSet}_{\\mathrm{bij}},\\mathbf{Set}]</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.0361em;vertical-align:-0.2861em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">[</span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">FinSet</span></span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3361em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathrm mtight\">bij</span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.2861em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbf\">Set</span></span><span class=\"mclose\">]</span></span></span></span>-enriched.)</p>",
